<br>
I suffer from allergies too.  I know when the allergist did the scratch test on my back, I reacted to ALL the airborne allergens they scratched me with.<br>
<br>
I went thru several years of allergy shots from the allergist, but the steps i took at home were crucial.  I went to Allergy Relief Store and bought special coverings for my mattress, pillows (discarded feather pillows as they are allergen nightmares) and box springs.  The special coverings actually form a barrier which dust and dust mites cannot pass.  Mattresses and upholstered furniture are the largest harborers of dust mites in the your home.  Consider discarding old sofas/couches...if you could see the dust clouds that burst from them when you plop down, you would never sit on a sofa again; if you don't want to discard anything, you have to keep it clean.   House dust is the NUMBER ONE allergen out there, so you want to get a handle on house dust.  Also bought a high quality, high efficiency filter for the Air-Conditioner.<br>
<br>
You probably have cats too.  Bad news there...you are prolly allergic to those precious little bundles as well.  Animal dander is brutal on your immune system, add that to the dust from the litter box (cat urine carries allergens too) and you get a sneeze bonanza.<br>
<br>
If you have carpets in your home, they are big allergen hangouts too.  Consider removing them or vacuuming often with a good vacuum cleaner that has efficient filtration.<br>
<br>
Clean your ceiling fans if you have them, and do not use them.  All they do is stir up allergens.<br>
<br>
Run your air conditioner, it helps remove airborne contaminants.  Also get your A/C professional to clean the &quot;coils&quot; on your A/C annually.  This area on the machine gets filthy with mold/mildew.<br>
<br>
Watch damp areas in the kitchen or bath.  Mold spores are HUGE irritants as well.  Bleach/Tilex rules these areas.<br>
<br>
Get a scrip from your doctor for Nasonex or Flonase which are once maybe twice daily nasal sprays which help tremendously.<br>
Claritin, Zyrtec and Allegra are helpful meds but usually the sprays are best with nearly no side effects.<br>
<br>
Hope this helps.  Bless you!<br>
